## 3. Insertion Sort

### Algorithm Description

Insertion Sort builds the sorted array one element at a time by **inserting** each new element into its correct position within the already-sorted portion. It mimics how most people naturally sort a hand of playing cards.

**Step-by-step:**
1. Treat `arr[0]` as a trivially sorted subarray of length 1.
2. Pick the next element `key = arr[i]` (the first element of the unsorted portion).
3. Compare `key` against elements in the sorted portion, moving right-to-left.
4. Shift every element that is greater than `key` one position to the right.
5. Insert `key` into the gap created.
6. Repeat steps 2–5 until all elements are processed.

**Key insight:** Insertion Sort is adaptive — it runs in O(n) when the array is nearly sorted. For small arrays or nearly-sorted data it outperforms O(n log n) algorithms due to its tiny constant factor and zero overhead. It is the preferred algorithm for arrays of size < ~10–20 in hybrid sorts like Timsort.

---

### Complexity Analysis

| Case | Time Complexity | Explanation |
|------|----------------|-------------|
| Best | O(n) | Already sorted; inner loop never executes |
| Average | O(n²) | ~n²/4 comparisons and shifts on average |
| Worst | O(n²) | Reverse-sorted; maximum shifts every step |

**Space Complexity: O(1)** — in-place sorting.

**Stability: Yes** — elements are only shifted past `key` if strictly greater, so equal elements retain their original order.

---

### Python Implementation

```python
def insertion_sort(arr):
    n = len(arr)

    # Start from index 1 — arr[0] is trivially sorted
    for i in range(1, n):

        # The element to be placed into the sorted portion
        key = arr[i]

        # Start comparing from the last element of the sorted portion
        j = i - 1

        # Shift elements of the sorted portion that are greater than key
        # one position to the right to make room for key
        while j >= 0 and arr[j] > key:
            arr[j + 1] = arr[j]  # Shift right
            j -= 1

        # Place key in its correct position
        # (j+1 because j was decremented one too many times)
        arr[j + 1] = key

    return arr
```

---

### Example Trace: `[64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]`

```
Initial:  [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]

--- Step i=1: key=34 ---
  Sorted portion: [64]
  64 > 34 → shift 64 right: [64, 64, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]
  j=-1, insert key at j+1=0
  Result: [34, 64, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]
  Sorted: [34, 64]

--- Step i=2: key=25 ---
  Sorted portion: [34, 64]
  64 > 25 → shift 64 right: [34, 64, 64, 12, 22, 11, 90]
  34 > 25 → shift 34 right: [34, 34, 64, 12, 22, 11, 90]
  j=-1, insert key at j+1=0
  Result: [25, 34, 64, 12, 22, 11, 90]
  Sorted: [25, 34, 64]

--- Step i=3: key=12 ---
  Sorted portion: [25, 34, 64]
  64 > 12 → shift: [25, 34, 64, 64, 22, 11, 90]
  34 > 12 → shift: [25, 34, 34, 64, 22, 11, 90]
  25 > 12 → shift: [25, 25, 34, 64, 22, 11, 90]
  j=-1, insert key at j+1=0
  Result: [12, 25, 34, 64, 22, 11, 90]
  Sorted: [12, 25, 34, 64]

--- Step i=4: key=22 ---
  Sorted portion: [12, 25, 34, 64]
  64 > 22 → shift: [12, 25, 34, 64, 64, 11, 90]
  34 > 22 → shift: [12, 25, 34, 34, 64, 11, 90]
  25 > 22 → shift: [12, 25, 25, 34, 64, 11, 90]
  12 < 22 → stop, insert key at j+1=1
  Result: [12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 11, 90]
  Sorted: [12, 22, 25, 34, 64]

--- Step i=5: key=11 ---
  Sorted portion: [12, 22, 25, 34, 64]
  64 > 11 → shift: [12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 64, 90]
  34 > 11 → shift: [12, 22, 25, 34, 34, 64, 90]
  25 > 11 → shift: [12, 22, 25, 25, 34, 64, 90]
  22 > 11 → shift: [12, 22, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]
  12 > 11 → shift: [12, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]
  j=-1, insert key at j+1=0
  Result: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]
  Sorted: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64]

--- Step i=6: key=90 ---
  Sorted portion: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64]
  64 < 90 → stop immediately, insert key at j+1=6
  Result: [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]  ← SORTED ✓
```

