## 9. Complexity Summary

| Algorithm | Best | Average | Worst | Space | Stable | In-Place | Notes |
|-----------|------|---------|-------|-------|--------|----------|-------|
| Bubble Sort | O(n) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | Yes | Yes | Best for nearly-sorted; never use otherwise |
| Selection Sort | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | No | Yes | Min swaps (≤ n-1); no early exit |
| Insertion Sort | O(n) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | Yes | Yes | Excellent for small/nearly-sorted arrays |
| Merge Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n) | Yes | No | Best stable sort; predictable |
| Quick Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n²) | O(log n) | No | Yes | Fastest in practice; avoid sorted inputs |
| Heap Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(1) | No | Yes | Guaranteed O(n log n), poor cache behavior |
| Counting Sort | O(n+k) | O(n+k) | O(n+k) | O(n+k) | Yes | No | Only integers; k = value range |
| Radix Sort | O(dn) | O(dn) | O(dn) | O(n+k) | Yes | No | Only integers; d = digit count |

### When to Use What

```
Is data a small integer range?
  Yes → Counting Sort or Radix Sort (linear time)
  No  → continue...

Is stability required?
  Yes → Merge Sort (general) or Insertion Sort (small/nearly-sorted)
  No  → continue...

Is memory a hard constraint?
  Yes → Heap Sort (O(1) space, guaranteed O(n log n))
  No  → continue...

Is the array small (n < 20) or nearly sorted?
  Yes → Insertion Sort
  No  → Quick Sort (fastest general-purpose average case)
```

### Real-World Usage
- **Python's `list.sort()` / `sorted()`** — Timsort: hybrid of Merge Sort + Insertion Sort
- **Java `Arrays.sort()` (primitives)** — Dual-pivot Quick Sort
- **Java `Collections.sort()` (objects)** — Timsort (stable required for objects)
- **C++ `std::sort`** — Introsort: hybrid Quick Sort + Heap Sort + Insertion Sort
- **Database ORDER BY** — Often Merge Sort variants (external sort for disk-based data)
